<p>Natural wines showcase terroir expression more transparently than conventional wines. <strong>Burgundian natural Pinot Noir</strong> displays crystalline red fruit and limestone minerality, while natural Barolo reveals tar, rose, and earth complexity through extended macerations. Quality indicators include aromatic purity, textural harmony, and the absence of reduction or volatile acidity faults that can plague poorly made natural wines.</p>

<p>The best examples demonstrate <strong>balance between fruit expression and microbial influence</strong>, avoiding the "funky" characteristics that can dominate inferior natural wines. Look for producers like Domaine de la Côte in California or Radikon in Friuli, whose wines command premium prices through consistent quality and distinctive regional character.</p>

